Since the re-opening of schools two weeks ago, more than 130,000 teachers took part in a national survey, to determine the prevalence of COVID-19-associated risk factors. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Tens of thousands of teachers have multiple medical conditions that are considered risks for COVID-19. Since the reopening of schools two weeks ago, more than 130,000 teachers took part in a national survey to determine the prevalence of COVID-19-associated risk factors. READ: Schools are not ready to reopen in June - Sadtu It revealed that more than 65,000 teachers reported having a single co-morbidity such as hypertension, asthma, and diabetes. The rest have multiple medical conditions. READ: Teacher Unions: No PPE, No work The survey was a self-administered online questionnaire sent to all educators belonging to the various teachers' unions. Since the reopening, several schools have had to close after teachers or pupils tested positive for COVID-19. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.